<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="141" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">
The holotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wei &amp; Yang" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Sarcophaga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sarcophaga catoptosa" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catoptosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Sarcophaga catoptosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is deposited in CDCP and not currently available for loan and study. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wei, LM" editor="Li, ZZ" journalOrPublisher="Guizhou Science and Technology Publishing House, Guiyang" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" pagination="526 - 539" refId="B42" refString="Wei, LM, Yang, ZH, 2007. Sarcophagidae. In: Li, ZZ, Yang, MF, Jin, DC, Eds., Insects from Leigongshan Landscape. Guizhou Science and Technology Publishing House, Guiyang: 526 - 539" title="Sarcophagidae." volumeTitle="Insects from Leigongshan Landscape." year="2007">Wei and Yang (2007)</bibRefCitation>
described the lateral styli as bifurcated at the base and expanded at the apex (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Sarcophaga (Cornexcisia) suthep Pape &amp; Baenziger, 2003; phallus, lateral view A adapted from Pape and Baenziger (2003) B adapted from Wei and Yang (2007, as Sarcophaga catoptosa)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.83267.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706068" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">3</figureCitation>
). This unique character in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1824" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Sarcophaga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sarcophaga" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Sarcophaga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is shared by 
<taxonomicName family="Sarcophagidae" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. suthep" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" rank="species" species="suthep">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">S. suthep</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and other species assigned to the subgenus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fan &amp; Kano" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Sarcophaga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sarcophaga (Cornexcisia)" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Cornexcisia">Sarcophaga Cornexcisia</taxonomicName>
. We consider the following compelling similarities between the nominal species 
<taxonomicName family="Sarcophagidae" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. suthep" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" rank="species" species="suthep">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">S. suthep</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName family="Sarcophagidae" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. catoptosa" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" rank="species" species="catoptosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">S. catoptosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, as assessed from the illustrations of the phallus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Sarcophaga (Cornexcisia) suthep Pape &amp; Baenziger, 2003; phallus, lateral view A adapted from Pape and Baenziger (2003) B adapted from Wei and Yang (2007, as Sarcophaga catoptosa)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1108.83267.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/706068" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">3</figureCitation>
), to justify the proposed synonymy: vesica of identical shape; juxta, harpes and lateral styli differing only by small differences in the outline, and this involves membranous parts that are often presenting themselves very differently due to shrinking during drying or other preparation. 
<bibRefCitation author="Wei, LM" editor="Li, ZZ" journalOrPublisher="Guizhou Science and Technology Publishing House, Guiyang" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" pagination="526 - 539" refId="B42" refString="Wei, LM, Yang, ZH, 2007. Sarcophagidae. In: Li, ZZ, Yang, MF, Jin, DC, Eds., Insects from Leigongshan Landscape. Guizhou Science and Technology Publishing House, Guiyang: 526 - 539" title="Sarcophagidae." volumeTitle="Insects from Leigongshan Landscape." year="2007">Wei and Yang (2007)</bibRefCitation>
stressed the following difference between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wei &amp; Yang" authorityYear="2007" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Sarcophaga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sarcophaga catoptosa" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catoptosa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Sarcophaga catoptosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pape &amp; Baenziger" authorityYear="2003" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Sarcophaga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sarcophaga suthep" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="suthep">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Sarcophaga suthep</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: the protuberance of former cerci is slightly narrower than the latter in dorsal view and the hind margin of former pregonite is wavy bending with a sharper tip, but those differences are minor. They still have the same shape, only varying in degree. Therefore, we consider these to be intraspecific differences.
</paragraph>
